In LaTeX, you can generate an automatic table of contents (TOC) using the `\tableofcontents` command and configuring sectioning elements with the appropriate labels. Here's an example:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\begin{document}

\tableofcontents % generates the TOC

\section{Introduction}\label{sec:intro}
Text for introduction.

\subsection{Background}\label{subsec:bg}
More text for background information.

\section{Methods}\label{sec:methods}
Description of methods used.

\appendix
\section{Additional Materials}\label{app:extra}
Supplementary materials.

\end{document}
```

In this example:

1. The `\documentclass{article}` line specifies the document class, which includes basic support for generating a table of contents.
2. The `\tableofcontents` command is placed at the desired location (usually near the beginning of the document) to generate the TOC.
3. Each sectioning element (e.g., `\section`, `\subsection`) is labeled using the `\label` command. This associates a unique label with each section, allowing LaTeX to include it in the TOC.

When you compile this document, LaTeX will automatically generate a table of contents that lists the sections and subsections, along with their corresponding page numbers.

Note: Make sure to run LaTeX twice (e.g., `pdflatex filename.tex` followed by `pdflatex filename.tex` again) to ensure that the TOC is updated correctly.

To draw a chessboard representing a FEN notation in LaTeX, you'll need to use a package specifically designed for creating diagrams or graphics. One popular option is `tikz`. Here's a minimal example code to get you started:
```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{matrix}

\newcommand{\chesssquare}[2]{%
  \node [draw, thick, rectangle, minimum size=1.2em] (#1) {#2};
}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}
  % Define the chessboard grid (8x8)
  \matrix [matrix of nodes, column sep=-\pgflinewidth, row sep=-\pgflinewidth] (board) {
    \foreach \row [count=\y] in {1,...,8} {
      \foreach \col [count=\x] in {a, b, c, d, e, f, g, h} {
        \chesssquare{\x-\y} {% empty square for now, replace with FEN piece notation
          % Example: \ifthenelse{\iswhite}{''}{\tiny\blackletterfont{}}
        }
      }
    }
  };
\end{tikzpicture}

% Customize appearance (optional)
\foreach \square in {(a-1), (h8)} % highlight edges
  \draw [thick] (\square.south west) -- (\square.south east);

\end{document}
```
Let's explain the code:

1. We include the `tikz` package and load the `matrix` library, which allows us to create a grid for the chessboard.
2. The `\chesssquare` command defines a single square node with a draw border, minimum size, and optional content (which will be replaced with FEN piece notation).
3. In the `tikzpicture` environment, we create an 8x8 matrix (`board`) using nested `foreach` loops to generate the squares.
4. For now, the squares are empty; you'll need to modify the code to insert FEN piece notation (e.g., 'N' for knight, 'Q' for queen, etc.) based on the specific board state.
5. The optional customization section draws thick lines along the edges of the board (highlighting them).

To use this code, replace the empty squares with the actual FEN piece notation. You can do this by adding conditional statements or using a separate data structure to store the FEN information and then inject it into the `\chesssquare` command.

Remember to adjust the font sizes and styles to your liking. This example uses a simple font for demonstration purposes. You may want to consider using a chess-specific font, like `\chessfont` from the `chessfont` package (if available).

